25|$|During the 1960s and 1970s, Georgia made {{significant}} changes <b>in</b> <b>civil</b> <b>rights</b> and governance. As {{in many other}} states, its legislature had not reapportioned congressional districts according to population from 1931 to after the 1960 census. Problems of malapportionment in the state legislature, where rural districts had outsize power in relation to urban districts, such as Atlanta's, were corrected after the US Supreme Court ruling in Wesberry v. Sanders (1964). The court ruled that congressional districts had to be reapportioned to have essentially equal populations.|$|E
